<ITEM>There is a con&s;entaneou&s;ne&s;s in &s;ome minds, which will unite them &s;tronger to each other in a few hours, than can be done in years with &s;ome others whom yet we &s;ee not with di&s;gu&s;t.</ITEM>
<ITEM>An active &s;pirit in one Friend, and a pa&s;&s;ive one in the other, is likely to make their Friend&s;hip durable.</ITEM>
<ITEM>A great error ought le&s;s to be excu&s;ed in one we value, than in one to whom we are indifferent.</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB N="246" REF="254">True Friend&s;hip will make a per&s;on careful to &s;hun every appearance that may tend to deba&s;e it by &s;elfi&s;h or &s;ordid views.</ITEM>
